                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d330">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/15355: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-22T16:00:00+07:00"
                            >April 22, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 22—2:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>705. For Department’s information, Hearn has recently received rather sharp
                    letter from Ho Ying-chin on subject of Department’s 333, March 13.<note n="19"
                        xml:id="d330fn19">See footnote 94, <ref target="#pg_373">p.
                        373</ref>.</note> Letter makes familiar accusation that Communists have not
                    obeyed Chinese Government orders and states that since American Army forces are
                    “representatives of the American Nation”, the request to visit Communist area
                    “cannot be considered” by Chinese Government; that Hearn is “well aware” that
                    “permission was granted” correspondents to visit area because they belong to
                    civilian organizations; that if Hearn desires to collect intelligence regarding
                    Japs in North China, “it can very well be done at appropriate places in the 1st,
                    2d and 8th War Areas where as much assistance as possible can be rendered with
                    comparative ease”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
